  <article>
    <h2>Do I still need to log an ITG?</h2>
    <strong>No.</strong>  An ITG is no longer required. If you wish, you can add such information in comments after ticket's workflow is crated.<br />
    <br />
 </article>
 
 <article>
    <h2>Why do I need to include a rollback script?</h2>
    In order to maintain Sarbox compliance, a rollback script is required for any change to the system.  The rollback script is validated in the same manner as the change script and will be executed if a change scripts does not execute properly.<br />
    <br /> 
    Yes, you can input an empty rollback script, or you can even download an empty script that does nothing but print datetime and process information from our <a href="/Template">template gallery</a>.
 </article>

 <article>
    <h2>Do I have to use the templates?</h2>
    Short answer is - "No, you don't and you are free to write any valid script.". <br />
    <br />
    But, we do encourage best practice of SQL coding style to output proper information to help the approver (who may not be tech savy person), your co-worker or even yourself to keep track of what's executing, and in case of failure you can quickly identify where it fails. It will certainly help you to debug your script without banging your head to the door. <br />    
    <br />
    Those templates are provided as guidance and convenient way of wrapping your SQL change, and it is written by highly skilled professionals, so we do recommend you to utilize them as much as you can.
 </article>

 <article>
    <h2>Why did validation fail?</h2>
    All target and rollback scripts are validated prior to execution.  The validation routine looks for types of scripts that would violate best practices, scripts that would attempt to break security policy, or scripts that are likely complex enough to require DBA review.  You may request the DBA team to execute the script on your behalf through the ITG process.<br />
    <br />
    Some common prohibited activity: <br />
    <ol>
        <li>Executing a CRUD operation without a where clause</li>
        <li>Dropping an object</li>
        <li>Truncating a table</li>
        <li>Executing dynamic SQL</li>
        <li>Changing the isolation level</li>
        <li>Backup or restore a database</li>
        <li>Executing a script on an alternate database</li>
        <li>Snapshot operations</li>
        <li>Alter the physical file structure</li>
        <li>Alter the resource governor</li>
        <li>Grant/Revoke access to the system</li>
        <li>Anything to do with Triggers</li>
        <li>Anything to do with SQL Jobs</li>
        <li>Changing the server configuration</li>
    </ol>
 </article>

 <article>
    <h2>Can I change a script that has been submitted?</h2>
    <strong>No,</strong> once submitted a script can not be changed.  This is to ensure audit compliance for all changes.<br />
    <br />
    You may cancel the current workflow and resubmit a new copy of the script.
 </article>

