 <article>
    <h2>Why am I unable to execute stored procedures?</h2>
    When executing stored procedures and functions, exclude the EXEC/EXECUTE keyword. You can execute your stored procedures and functions just by calling their names. Specifically, it is the&#160;&quot;EXEC&quot; and&#160;&quot;sp_execute&quot; keywords that the SSS Tool prevents. This was to prevent execution of invalid SQL using the Self Service SQL tool.
 </article>

 <article>
    <h2>Can one individual be an Approver and a Requester?</h2>
    Yes. Approvers, by default, can log SSS tickets.
 </article>

 <article>
    <h2>Can an Approver approve a ticket he or she submitted?</h2>
    No, script executions in SSS will always require two people. One purpose of this is to ensure that the script to be executed is reviewed by another.
 </article>

 <article>
    <h2>Can an Approvers continue the workflow of another Approver?</h2>
    Yes. Assuming Approver 1 executed a script in staging and went on holiday. Approver 2, who is available, may execute the script in production.
 </article>

 <article>
    <h2>It says &quot;Dangerous SQL Detected,&quot; how do we know what caused the validation error?</h2>
    Check the error message in the &quot;Raw Logs&quot; tab.  It will list the reason for the script failing validation.  The script can then be corrected and resubmitted
 </article>

 <article>
    <h2>How long can we put a SSS ticket on hold?</h2>
    Release 1.1 has no limit on the time between workflow steps.  A future release may automatically close any open tickets 60 days after original upload.
 </article>

